&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;SELECT id_customer, surname, name, id_dir, address
FROM CustomersAddress
INNER JOIN Customers ON Customers.id=CustomersAddress.id_customer
INNER JOIN Address ON Address.id_dir=CustomersAddress.id_address
ORDER BY FIELD(id_dir, 2,4,3,5,1), surname;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;SQLFiddle example - &lt;a href="http://sqlfiddle.com/#!2/3ea9c/18" rel="nofollow"&gt;http://sqlfiddle.com/#!2/3ea9c/18&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;this would require either a subquery or a prequery to get the order.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;'SELECT emp from table emp=\'$sid\''&lt;/code&gt; is a string that you pass exactly as it is to Oracle, this is why it doesn't work.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You need to use &lt;a href="http://php.net/manual/en/function.oci-bind-by-name.php" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;code&gt;oci_bind_by_name&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt; to bind a placeholder to a PHP variable.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;$variable = 42;
$stid = oci_parse($conn, 'SELECT col_name FROM tbl_name WHERE col_name &amp;gt; :num;');
oci_bind_by_name($stid, ":num", $variable);
oci_execute($stid);
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

